included.customDescription: This project investigated the effect that context has on spatial abilities, more specifically mental rotation. It investigated how humans mentally rotated objects in an underwater environment.
included.description: Fifty-Six undergraduates completed a series of mental rotation exercises involving levels of underwater spatial mental model activation. The mental rotation exercises were performed after achieving ninety percent accuracy on a brief training exercise. It tested whether underwater experience had an effect on mental rotation performance. Same/different responses were measured using reaction time and accuracy.
included.customTitle: The Mental Rotation of Objects Presented in an Underwater Environment

included.description:
I led a human factors project team that was focused on designing and researching an interface for an autonomous robot. 

As project lead, I led UX research efforts and display design in addition to coordinating interface development with AI and software engineering groups. 

Using my knowledge of machine learning and data mining, I created foundational user centered design principles for autonomous system display design. 

I created interface prototypes, storyboards, and mock-ups for user testing using Adobe Photoshop and Illustrator

My role was to develop project plans, write research articles, conduct statistical analyses, define user performance indices, design the display, analyze operator workflows, develop the research study design, conduct usability analysis, produce user training materials, coordinate qualitative/quantitative user testing, present findings at meetings, and deliver study reports to stakeholders

I evangelized research in presentations, posters, and publications
included.title: Postdoctoral Human Factors Researcher/Project Lead

included.description:
I designed small group instructional materials to train adult learners on using statistical software. By the end of the training period the learners were able to competently navigate through utilizing the basic statistical methods of the software. 
I conducted needs assessments for learners. 
I Created and assessed learning via online modules for scientific writing
Grading and reviewing research reports on the guidelines of APA style and scientific writing
Worked on interactive digital instruction modules for online classes. The modules were made to represent and teach students how to analyze classic psychological experiments.
included.title: Graduate Teaching Assistant

included.description: I was the principal Investigator on four research studies investigating visual cognition, display clutter, and spatial ability. Through the course of my graduate career, I developed a new and unique research hypothesis investigating spatial processing and complex visual images. This novel method spawned a line of research in spatial abilities involving context and 6 different factors in visual complexity. I led 4 groups of 3-5 junior research assistants in formal research methodology and participant recruitment procedure. Scheduling and recruitment for over 300 face-to-face participants was coordinated over the course of several months.The data were analyzed using mixed ANOVA, ANCOVA, MANOVA, and multivariate regression. It was found that participants showed less difficulty in spatially processing objects when presented in a familiar environment.

included.description:
I lead user experience research on consumer, enterprise, mobile, and marketing websites

My primary responsibility is to identify a key product need, and gather data on user pain points.

I collaborate in the development, integration, and redesigns of the product and features to advocate for users.

I deliver presentations , research reports and evangelize the research results across the company.

When developing user studies, I collaborate with designers, product managers, marketing, and engineering to ensure studies produce results that will be accepted across the company.

Quantitative and qualitative research methodologies include: moderated usability testing, survey design, card sorting, remote usability testing, A/B testing, and contextual inquiry.

Results include qualitative user feedback and needs, system usability scores, product desirability, task time, task errors, task difficulty, and ease of use.

In addition to user research, I create wireframes for product implementation using Sketch, Axure, Photoshop, and Illustrator. 

I process participant videos using Adobe Premiere for fantastic presentations and archives of user studies.

included.summary:
Within me you'll find an unabashed passion for delivering delightful user experiences and examining the root cause for how users interact with your product. My love of cats is only trumped by my passion for investigating how humans interact with technology.  

I have over 12 years of experience conducting quantitative and qualitative studies to examine user behavior and applying UX principles to the design of interfaces. Previously, I designed and conducted UX research on a display for an autonomous robot with the Human Agent Teaming Lab (division of  Army Research Lab). 

My current position is Senior User Experience Researcher at Malwarebytes. I conduct studies and gather user data to promote data driven UX across the organization. 

In my spare time, you can find me hitting the trails on my mountain bike, leveling up my video game skills, or spotting continuity errors in Star Trek.

Specialities: UX research, UX design, AI systems, robots, qualitative/quantitative data analysis and collection, ethnography, statistics, machine learning analysis, Lean UX, SPSS,  R programming, Python, Adobe Illustrator, Photoshop, and Premiere, Sketch, Axure.

included.description: The project investigates the role that environmental context plays in how we process objects spatially. I formulated the hypotheses and conducted the literature search. As the project manager I coordinated groups of 2-4 undergraduate research assistants in the running of participants and data analysis. I also developed and created the visual stimuli presented to the subjects. Over the course of the project we collected 100+ subjects. This project has resulted in both conference proceedings and poster presentations. It is currently in development to be published in a peer reviewed journal.
included.title: Investigating the effects of context on the spatial processing of objects

included.description: We use the Situation awareness-based Agent Transparency model as a framework to design a user interface to support agent transparency. Participants were asked to monitor the status of an autonomous robotic agent as it traversed simulated urban environments. During this task, participants were exposed to one of three levels of information used to support agent transparency in the interface display. Our findings suggest that providing agent transparency information allows operators to properly calibrate trust without excess workload. Though, increased agent transparency information did not support operator situation awareness.
included.title: The Effects of Agent Transparency on Human Robot Interaction

included.description: My dissertation investigated the effects of familiarizing individuals with either an object or background and the effects of this familiarity on a spatial manipulation task. Results indicated that background familiarity had the strongest effect on the manipulation of an object in front of it. Implications from this study can be extrapolated to spatial training procedures, virtual reality displays, and augmented reality displays.
included.title: Spatial Abilities, clutter, and training

included.description: The goal of the project was to investigate the use of a non-conventional sketching based training system to improve spatial abilities. It also investigated how encoding using gestures and sketching affects spatial cognition. As project lead I developed the training methodology, performed the data analyses, ran the participants, and presented the results at the annual meeting for the Association for Psychological Science. I also used eye tracking for the physiological analysis of the training results.
included.title: Investigating a sketching based method to train basic spatial abilities

included.description: The design and research of an interface for an autonomous robot. The project involved establishing interface requirements through interviews with stakeholders, engineers, and AI researchers. Then translation of those requirements into user centered wire frames. Wire frames went through iterative design sessions and then higher fidelity mockups were created. The high fidelity mockups were tested through usability evaluation methods such as card sorting and participatory walkthroughs. Results were translated into design recommendations and implemented into software interfaces. Software interfaces then went through testing to evaluate product specific goals such as trust, situation awareness, and workload. Results were presented to stake holders and published in conference proceedings/journal articles.
included.title: Autonomous Squad Member Year 2

included.name: From TVs to Phones A Comparison of Adultsâ Mental Models of Computers in 1999 and 2009
included.description: The mental models that participants had about the common technological device of a computer were examined in 1999 and 2009. The participants were prompted with the question âWhat is like a computer?â in order to generate analogies that were used to access their mental models. Results indicated that more analogies were generated in 1999 rather than 2009. In addition there was a reduction in the amount of analogies generated by males. The top popular analogies produced in 1999 and 2009 were found to be different. These results suggest that the general knowledge base people have about computers has shifted in the past decade. Further, the individual differences that one has may impact their beliefs and knowledge about computers.

included.name: The Effects of Agent Transparency on Human Interaction with an Autonomous Robotic Agent
included.description: We use the Situation awareness-based Agent Transparency model as a framework to design a user interface to support agent transparency. Participants were instructed to supervise an autonomous robotic agent as it traversed simulated urban environments. During this task, participants were exposed to one of three levels of information used to support agent transparency in the interface display. Our findings suggest that providing agent transparency information allows operators to properly calibrate trust without excess workload. Though, increased agent transparency information did not support operator situation awareness.

included.name: Agent Transparency for an Autonomous Squad Member
included.description: The ability to understand the reasoning behind an intelligent agentâs actions can help to increase operator performance as the use of human-agent teams for military operations grows. This experiment tested the effect of display design to convey environment and intelligent agent information in a simulation-based unmanned ground vehicle monitoring task. Three groups were tested with visual displays representing 1 of 3 types of information: current status only (group 1); current status with reasoning information (group 2); and current status, reasoning information, and projected information (group 3). Performance measures included comprehension of situation awareness probes, operator trust based on 3 different surveys, workload, and system usability. Results indicated a significant interaction between conditions and pre- and postadministration of a trust survey modified from Jian et al. (2000), with only group 2 increasing in trust preexperiment in comparison with postexperiment. The situation awareness probes failed to yield any significant differences among the conditions. No significant effects of operator workload or individual difference factors were observed across conditions. This research demonstrates the potential of agent transparency displays to improve Soldier trust and situation awareness.
